; Plowing Ceremony On the first day of the festival, the "Plowing Ceremony" takes place in front of the worship hall. Leading the procession is the head of seedlings, followed by ox handlers guiding oxen adorned with {{ill|Five-colored silk|ja|五色絹|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} yoked to a plow. Behind them are girls wearing {{ill|Scarlet hakama|ja|緋の袴|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, carrying sickles; men in {{ill|Hitatare|ja|直垂|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, holding plows and hoes; and eight girls dressed in white with scarlet hakama, wearing floral sashes and carrying flower hats on their backs. Additionally, eight children in ceremonial attire, representing the {{ill|Ta-no-Kami|lt=Deity of rice fields|ja|田の神|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, are carried on shoulders under floral umbrellas. The ceremony includes symbolic actions of inserting sickles, plows, and hoes, followed by plowing by the oxen. The eight girls then perform a ritual dance with seedlings handed to them by the head of seedlings, and the older rice-planting assistants carry out planting gestures, concluding the "Plowing Ceremony."
; Rice-Planting Ceremony On the second day, the "Rice-Planting Ceremony" is performed. Similar to the previous day, participants such as ceremonial sweepers, hoe handlers, elderly women, and children under ceremonial umbrellas gather in front of the worship hall. After a ritual dance by the girls, accompanied by rice-planting songs, the rice-planting assistants perform symbolic planting actions. Following the rituals at the worship hall, the participants proceed from the {{ill|Shrine approach|ja|参道|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the {{ill|Sacred rice field|ja|御田|1=Sacred rice field|1=Sacred rice field|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where further ceremonies, including offerings and prayer recitals, are conducted. The rice-planting assistants then plant rice in the sacred field while singing traditional rice-planting songs.
